<div class="full-post-footer  post-starter "></div>
    </li>
            <li class="content-item">
        




<div class="full-post-header "></div>
<div class="full-post-container fiji-full-post-container evolution2-full-post-container"  data-reply-id="824493"  data-thread-starter="false" >
<div class="full-post ">
	<a name="824493"></a>
	<a name="824493"></a>
	<div class="post-author">
		<table class="post-author-details-table fiji-post-author-details-table evolution2-post-author-details-table" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
			<tr>
				<td class="post-author-avatar-cell fiji-post-author-avatar-cell evolution2-post-author-avatar-cell">
					<span class="avatar">
													<a href="/members/grogg">
								<img src="/cfs-filesystemfile/__key/communityserver-components-imagefileviewer/communityserver-components-selectableavatars-64e6583d-e9be-44d9-a227-06c829b8c238/avatar.png_2D00_32x32.png" border="0" alt="Grogg" />
							</a>
											</span>
				</td>
				<td class="post-author-user-cell fiji-post-author-user-cell evolution2-post-author-user-cell">
				   <div class="user-name-post-date fiji-user-name-post-date evolution2-user-name-post-date">
						Posted by <span class="user-name">
															<a class="internal-link view-user-profile" href="/members/grogg">
									<span></span>Grogg
								</a>
													</span>
						<div class="post-date">
							<span class="label">
																	<a href="/cancer_types/breast-cancer/f/38/t/100606">on</a>
															</span>
							<span class="value"><a href='/cancer_types/breast-cancer/f/38/p/100606/824493#824493' class="internal-link view-post">30 Oct 2015 2:30 AM</a></span>
						</div>
																	</div>
				</td>
			</tr>
		</table>
	</div>
	
	
	<div class="post-content user-defined-markup">
					<p>First thing - please don&#39;t tell her how helpless you feel, how upset you all are etc.&nbsp; It&#39;s bad enough dealing with your own diagnosis but then you have to deal with family and friends reaction which make you feel as if they have written you off.&nbsp;&nbsp; She needs time to accept her diagnosis, she knows you are all shocked and upset but she&#39;s not in a place to comfort you at this moment.</p>
<p>Secondly - remember that while she will physically recover she will never feel the same again.&nbsp; There is a thread on here &quot;why am I not delighted&quot;.&nbsp; Have a read of this and you will gain some insight into how it affects people emotionally.</p>
<p>On a practical note for surgery there&#39;s lots of advice on this board about front opening PJs, soft bras, pillows for underarm etc.</p>
<p>I didn&#39;t have chemo only surgery and radiotherapy but have a read through the various discussions or use search facility.&nbsp; Else post your specific questions or better still encourage your SIL to join the community where she can get great support from other members.</p>
<p>She should be allocated a Breast Care Nurse.&nbsp; Most patients find these nurses very helpful and a great point of contact for any queries.&nbsp; She should give her advice pre surgery and look after her post surgery.&nbsp; Mine told me at first meeting she was now my advocate and if I needed anything she would act on my behalf.&nbsp; She&#39;s been an absolutely brilliant throughout the journey.</p>
<p>You know your SIL and it&#39;s great you wish to support her but try to take your lead from her.&nbsp; Does she liked to be fussed - I don&#39;t but some people do.&nbsp; Try to&nbsp; treat her as normal but offer to do practical things like shopping, the odd meal, a walk or a drive for a change of scenery.</p>
<p>There will be lots of hospital appointments that she may need lifts to.&nbsp; If you can,&nbsp;offer your services to share the load.&nbsp; She might want someone to attend appointments with her to ensure she asks all her questions and to ascertain she heard the answers.&nbsp;My BCN came out to my home to go over my diagnosis with myself and my family and it was a chance for us all to ask questions after we had time to digest the news.</p>
<p>I think most people on this site will say there are people who have been a great support, and people who don&#39;t know what to do so ignore you!!&nbsp; I&#39;ve been surprised and annoyed&nbsp;at the friends who tell me very infrequently &quot;they don&#39;t know how to deal with the situation&quot;,&nbsp; They drop me a text once a month out of obligation I feel.&nbsp; I&#39;ve been equally surprised and comforted by the others who text me daily, invite me to meet, ask can they do anything for me.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I&#39;ve been blessed in that all my family have been brilliant, especially my husband and daughter when I&#39;ve been crabby and mean.</p>
<p>Remember your SIL is not dying of cancer she&#39;s living with cancer but within a few months they will have ridden her breast of the cancer.&nbsp; BC is very treatable it&#39;s just a shame the treatment makes you ill whereas you were well before the found the ruddy disease!</p>
<p>I&#39;m sure others will come along with more advice and I&#39;m sure your SIL would benefit from joining when she feels ready.&nbsp; I wish someone had pointed me in the direction of this site early on as Mr Google is not your friend!</p>
<p>Right going to try to sleep now. Take care x</p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p></p><div style="clear:both;"></div>
					</div>

	



	  
