						Posted by <span class="user-name">
															<a class="internal-link view-user-profile" href="/members/crystaljuju">
									<span></span>Crystaljuju
								</a>
													</span>
						<div class="post-date">
							<span class="label">
																	<a href="/cancer_types/breast-cancer/f/38/t/100606">on</a>
															</span>
							<span class="value"><a href='/cancer_types/breast-cancer/f/38/p/100606/824507#824507' class="internal-link view-post">30 Oct 2015 8:09 AM</a></span>
						</div>
																	</div>
				</td>
			</tr>
		</table>
	</div>
	
	
	<div class="post-content user-defined-markup">
					<p>Hello Cheesie&nbsp;</p>
<p>im sorry your sister in law has been diagnosis. It&#39;s always s shock to be told you have cancer and a shock for those around you.&nbsp;</p>
<p>You sound close to your sister in law? In which case be guided by her over the support she would like from you. Talk about it. This is a sensitive area though. If you know her well you will know how to converse with her. Personally I found my friends and family&#39;s positivity &nbsp;helped me the most.&nbsp;</p>
<p>There is lots you can do to help. Cook dinners after she&#39;s had surgery and take them round to the family. Help with the housework, take some good books for her to read or films. Take her some hand cream, her favourite chocolate, any little taken of thought. The treatment process for me took 10 months so the support will be ongoing. Don&#39;t forget her husband and family will need support too.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The ten years you are referring to may mean she will be offered drugs for upto ten years after treatment. Some BC types (there are different types) have preventative drugs that you take. This reduces the risk of recurrence.&nbsp;</p>
<p>I would say suggest this forum to your SIL because we can all chat first hand then.&nbsp;</p>
<p>In the meantime you have every reason to stay positive. The survival statistics for BC are some of the best.&nbsp;</p>
<p>All the best x</p><div style="clear:both;"></div>
					</div>

	



	  
