	<div class="post-content user-defined-markup">
					<p>Dear Cheesie,</p>
<p>What a lovely sister-in-law you sound.&nbsp; You&#39;ve had lots of sound advice, with which I&#39;m pretty much in agreement.&nbsp; I also have a lovely sister-in-law.&nbsp; Pity she and my brother live in Denmark but here&#39;s what she did for me...listened attentively to the occasional moan, gave me therapeutic massages (that&#39;s what she does for a living), cooked great meals, didn&#39;t nag about seeing me with a glass of wine in my hand (you get so much unsolicited advice during cancer treatment).&nbsp; I&#39;m 18 months on from initial diagnosis and like many people here have been through the ringer...mastectomy, chemo, radiotherapy, more surgery and lots of medication.&nbsp; When I moved home recently (from London to Hastings), my brother and lovely wife came for several days, packed, organised, carried, shopped, cooked, calmed a traumatised cat (she&#39;s a &#39;cat-whisperer&#39;) then repeated the process&nbsp;after&nbsp;driving me to my &nbsp;new home.</p>
<p>My sister-in-law and I did lots of the &#39;normal&#39; stuff together, like going to car boot sales, buying lots of rubbish together and generally laughing&nbsp; a lot.&nbsp; As we&#39;ve always done.&nbsp; I have no sisters (4 brothers!) but she&#39;s the sister I would have asked for.&nbsp; </p>
<p>Best of everything to you, Cheesie,</p>
<p>Pepys xx</p><div style="clear:both;"></div>
					</div>

	



	  
